<h2>Best Varieties for Short Seasons</h2>
<p>
        Choose bolt-resistant varieties for late spring, and cold-tolerant types for fall.
      </p>
<ul>
<li>Slow-bolting types for warmer spring windows</li>
<li>Cold-tolerant types for fall planting</li>
<li>Baby-leaf mixes for quick, repeat harvests</li>
</ul>
<p class="fine muted">
        Spinach is sensitive to heat. Shade and moisture help in late spring.
      </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
<h2>Common Short-Season Mistakes</h2>
<ul>
<li><strong>Sowing too late in spring.</strong> Heat triggers bolting and bitterness.</li>
<li><strong>Letting soil dry out.</strong> Consistent moisture improves germination and leaf quality.</li>
<li><strong>Planting fall spinach too late.</strong> It needs time to size up before cold slows growth.</li>
</ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
<h2>Fall Planning Notes</h2>
<p>
        Fall spinach can be very productive if planted early enough. Growth slows as days shorten,
        so start sooner than you think.
      </p>
<ul>
<li>Plan fall sowing so plants size up before hard cold</li>
<li>Row cover can extend harvest and protect leaves</li>
<li>Harvest outer leaves regularly for longer production</li>
</ul>
<p>
        Use the <a href="/tools/first-frost-planner/">First Frost Planner</a> to estimate a last sow window.
      </p>
</section>

